85","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1290":"1290","Abt 1175":"about 1175","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","about 1210":"about 1210","1219":"1219","Thurrock, Essex, England,":"Thurrock, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Wrentham, Suffolk, England":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England","Codnor, Derbyshire, England":"Codnor, Derbyshire, England","Whatton, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Gray  .","German: dialect variant of   Grau  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Ukrainian <b>Grushko</b>: nickname or topographic name derived from a Russian-influenced transliteration of <i>grushka</i> ‘pear, pear tree’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gray","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (especially Eastern Ulster; of Norman origin): habitational name from Graye in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Graec(i)us</i>, meaning ‘Greek’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Greiwe","meanings":["German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>greibe</i> ‘sharp, tangy, dour’. Compare   Grey  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":84,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":115,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Grey was born about 1175, in Codnor, Derbyshire, England, her father, John de Grey, was 27 and her mother, Hawise de Clare, was 27. She had at least 2 sons with Wakelin d'Oyly."},"et":{"Abt 1175–":"umbes 1175–Surnud","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1176–1219":"1176–1219","1185–1230":"1185–1230","1195–1267":"1195–1267","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1150–1214":"1150–1214","1150–1215":"1150–1215","about 1195":"umbes 1195","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1164":"1164","1163":"1163","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1290":"1290","Abt 1175":"umbes 1175","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1219":"1219","Thurrock, Essex, England,":"Thurrock, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wrentham, Suffolk, England":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England","Codnor, Derbyshire, England":"Codnor, Derbyshire, England","Whatton, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1175–":"noin 1175–Kuollut","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1176–121